<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Andhra Pradesh</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">The <em>Rice Bowl of India</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Andhra Pradesh — the Land of Telugu People — is one of the Indian subcontinent's oldest continuous civilizations. The Telugu language, with a literary tradition stretching back over 1,000 years, is the third most spoken language in India and the 15th most spoken on earth. The state occupies the fertile delta of the Krishna and Godavari rivers — two of India's greatest sacred rivers — which together create one of the most productive agricultural landscapes in Asia. This is the Rice Bowl of India: the delta's emerald paddy fields stretch to every horizon, flooded mirror-lakes under monsoon skies. The Satavahana Empire, which once ruled all of central India, made Andhra Pradesh its cultural heartland. The Buddhist civilization that flourished here — at Amaravati, Nagarjunakonda and Guntupalle — was one of the greatest in Asia: the Amaravati School of sculpture, dating to the 1st century BC, produced stone carvings of a sensuous grace that influenced Buddhist art across Southeast Asia. The Vijayanagara Empire's cultural reach extended deep into Andhra; the Eastern Chalukyas of Vengi, the Kakatiyas and the Nayakas all built extraordinary temple traditions that endure in the Tirumala-Tirupati complex — the world's most visited religious site, receiving 60,000–100,000 pilgrims daily. Tirupati's Venkateswara temple is the wealthiest religious institution on earth. Andhra Pradesh's cuisine is among India's boldest — the fiery Andhra curries using Guntur chilies (the world's most traded chili variety) are renowned globally. The state's Kuchipudi classical dance, the Kondapalli toy craft, Kalamkari textile painting and the Bobbili veena represent living traditions of extraordinary refinement. Amaravati — AP's new capital being built on the Krishna riverfront — is one of the world's most ambitious planned city projects. With 975 km of coastline (India's second longest), diverse tribal cultures in the Eastern Ghats, and the sacred rivers connecting everything, Andhra Pradesh is where ancient rivers and ancient prayers have never stopped flowing.</p>
</section>
