const placesData=[
{emoji:"🛕",name:"Tirumala Venkateswara Temple",location:"Tirupati, Chittoor District",desc:"The world's most visited religious site and wealthiest temple — 60,000 to 100,000 pilgrims climb the seven sacred hills to the Venkateswara (Balaji) shrine every single day. The temple's annual income exceeds Rs.3,000 crore. The pre-dawn darshan in the crush of devoted humanity, the thundering of the bells, the aroma of camphor and the sight of the golden vimana tower are overwhelming. A pilgrimage that transforms the devotee.",fee:["Free (Special darshan paid)"]},
{emoji:"🏺",name:"Amaravati Buddhist Stupa",location:"Guntur District",desc:"One of the greatest Buddhist monuments in India — the Great Stupa of Amaravati (3rd century BC to 3rd century AD) was the largest stupa in ancient India. Though the original stupa was dismantled, its extraordinary sculptural panels are now in the British Museum and the Chennai Museum. The site's Amaravati Museum preserves the civilizational memory of one of ancient Asia's greatest Buddhist kingdoms.",fee:["Rs.25 Indians","Rs.300 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🏔️",name:"Araku Valley & Borra Caves",location:"Visakhapatnam District",desc:"A breathtaking highland valley at 900 meters in the Eastern Ghats — terraced coffee and pepper plantations, tribal Kondh and Bagata villages, waterfalls and the extraordinary Borra Caves (10 million-year-old limestone caverns, 80 meters deep, with stalactites and stalagmites of cathedral scale). The Araku Valley Express train journey through 58 tunnels and 84 bridges is one of India's most scenic rail trips.",fee:["Borra Caves: Paid"]},
{emoji:"🕌",name:"Lepakshi Temple Complex",location:"Anantapur District",desc:"A 16th-century Vijayanagara temple of extraordinary grace — the Veerabhadra Temple at Lepakshi has a hanging pillar (one of 70 columns) that does not rest on the ground and a colossal monolithic Nandi (sacred bull) — the largest in India. The ceiling paintings in the natya mantapa (dance hall) are among the finest examples of Vijayanagara fresco art, covering 8,000 sq ft in vibrant red, black and green.",fee:["Rs.15 Indians","Rs.200 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🏰",name:"Gandikota — Grand Canyon of India",location:"Kadapa District",desc:"The Penna river cuts through the Erramala Hills creating a dramatic 2 km gorge overlooked by the ruins of the 13th-century Gandikota Fort. The canyon at sunrise — the river glinting in the gorge below, the ancient fort walls above, the Rayalaseema plateau stretching away — is one of South India's most spectacular natural scenes. Almost entirely undiscovered by mass tourism.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🌊",name:"Godavari River — Papikondalu Gorge",location:"East Godavari-West Godavari",desc:"The Godavari — the Dakshin Ganga — cuts through the Eastern Ghats creating the spectacular Papikondalu gorge before spreading into the world's second-largest river delta. Boat journeys through the gorge pass forested hills, tribal villages and the meeting points of ancient pilgrimage routes. The Godavari Pushkaram (every 12 years) draws millions to its banks for the most sacred bathing festival in AP.",fee:["Boat charges apply"]},
{emoji:"🐯",name:"Nagarjunasagar-Srisailam Tiger Reserve",location:"Kurnool-Guntur-Nalgonda",desc:"India's largest tiger reserve — 3,568 sq km of forest across two states, named for the ancient Buddhist site of Nagarjunakonda and the Srisailam Mallikarjuna Jyotirlinga. The reserve shelters tigers, leopards, wild dogs and the endemic slender loris in the Nallamala forest. The Krishna river gorge within the reserve is dramatically beautiful.",fee:["Paid"]},
{emoji:"🌺",name:"Sri Kalahasthi — Vayu Linga",location:"Chittoor District",desc:"One of the Pancha Bhuta Stalas — the five temples representing the five elements. Srikalahasthi is the Vayu (wind/air) linga. The spider, snake and elephant who performed puja to the self-manifested Shivalinga are sculpted in gold at the entrance. The Rahu-Ketu puja performed here is unique in India — thousands come specifically for this astrological remedy.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🗿",name:"Undavalli Rock-Cut Caves",location:"Vijayawada, Krishna District",desc:"4th–5th century Buddhist and Hindu rock-cut caves carved from a single sandstone hill on the Krishna riverbank — 4 stories of chambers containing a colossal reclining Vishnu carved from a single rock. The setting — the river below, the rising hills — and the quality of the carvings make Undavalli one of AP's most beautiful and underappreciated monuments.",fee:["Rs.15 Indians","Rs.200 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🦅",name:"Pulicat Lake — Second Largest Brackish Lake",location:"Nellore-Sriharikota Border",desc:"India's second-largest brackish water lake and the winter home of thousands of flamingos, pelicans, painted storks and migratory ducks. Sriharikota — the satellite launch center — lies on the strip of land separating Pulicat from the sea. Fishing communities have lived around this lake for centuries; their catamaran boats and ancient fishing techniques create a timeless coastal scene.",fee:["Free"]}
