const artsData=[
{emoji:"💃",name:"Kuchipudi Classical Dance",location:"Kuchipudi Village, Krishna District",desc:"One of India's eight classical dance forms — originating in the village of Kuchipudi in Krishna district, where Brahmin men performed exclusively for centuries. Characterized by fast-paced footwork, fluid body movements and expressive mime (abhinaya). The Tarangam — performed on a brass plate while balancing a pot of water on the head — is a uniquely Kuchipudi virtuoso technique. UNESCO recognized, globally performed."},
{emoji:"🖼️",name:"Kalamkari — Pen Drawing on Cloth",location:"Srikalahasthi and Machilipatnam",desc:"An ancient craft of painting stories on cloth using a bamboo pen (kalam) dipped in natural dyes. Two distinct traditions: Srikalahasthi's freehand Kalamkari depicting temple stories, and Machilipatnam's block-printed geometric patterns. Both use only natural dyes — pomegranate, indigo, turmeric, iron rust. UNESCO-recognized GI-tagged craft now internationally exhibited as a major textile art."},
{emoji:"🪆",name:"Kondapalli Toys",location:"Kondapalli, Krishna District",desc:"Brightly painted wooden toys carved from softwood (tella poniki) in the village of Kondapalli — deities, animals, village scene figures and mythological characters painted in bold primary colors. A 400-year-old GI-tagged craft tradition where every family is a specialist. The distinctive stylization — elongated, flowing forms with characteristic color combinations — is immediately recognizable."},
{emoji:"🎵",name:"Carnatic Music — AP's Classical Tradition",location:"Statewide",desc:"Andhra Pradesh is the homeland of several Carnatic music composers of the highest rank. Annamacharya (1408–1503) of Tirupati composed over 32,000 keertanas dedicated to Venkateswara — the greatest corpus of devotional music by a single composer in the world. Tyagaraja spent his life in AP. The Telugu language's natural musicality — all words ending in vowels — made it the ideal vehicle for Carnatic composition."},
{emoji:"🧵",name:"Pochampally Ikat & Dharmavaram Silk",location:"Pochampally (now Telangana edge) and Dharmavaram",desc:"Dharmavaram silk sarees — woven in Anantapur district with pure zari borders and rich jewel-colored silk — are among India's most prized bridal sarees. The weavers of Dharmavaram have been producing these for the Tirupati temple and royal courts for centuries. GI-tagged. The town is considered South India's silk capital after Kanchipuram."},
{emoji:"🎭",name:"Burra Katha & Harikatha",location:"Statewide",desc:"Burra Katha — an extraordinary narrative folk performance where a lead performer and two assistants sing, mime and narrate stories of Telugu heroes, social issues and mythology to village audiences. The lead performer wears a turban and plays a burra (clay pot drum). Harikatha — devotional storytelling with music — has been practiced for centuries as a vehicle for both religious teaching and social commentary."}
