const cuisinesData=[
{emoji:"🌶️",name:"Andhra Spice — The Hottest Cuisine in India",region:"Statewide — Guntur Chili Heritage",desc:"Andhra Pradesh produces the Guntur chili — the world's most traded chili variety, used in cuisines from South Korea to Morocco. AP cooking uses chili not just for heat but for color, aroma and depth. The state's curries are among the hottest in the world by design — not carelessness. Andhra spice culture is a philosophy: the fire clears the palate and makes the body feel alive."},
{emoji:"🍛",name:"Andhra Biryani",region:"Hyderabad-influenced, Statewide",desc:"Andhra biryani differs from Hyderabadi in its use of more whole spices, mirchi ka salan and a firmer, more distinct rice-and-meat layering. The Guntur variant uses more chili in the marination. The coastal variants use prawns and fish. The Rayalaseema version is drier and fiercer. Each region of AP has its own biryani character — sharing the technique but expressing a distinct Telugu heat identity."},
{emoji:"🫕",name:"Pesarattu & Upma",region:"Coastal Andhra",desc:"The quintessential AP breakfast combination — whole green moong dal ground into a crispy crepe (pesarattu) and served with a mound of upma stuffed inside plus ginger chutney alongside. The pesarattu is fiercely green, tangy from fermentation and protein-rich. A dish of extraordinary nutritional density that has sustained coastal Telugu families for generations. Eaten at every tiffin center in AP."},
{emoji:"🍲",name:"Gongura Chicken & Mutton",region:"Coastal Andhra — Statewide",desc:"Gongura (Kenaf / roselle leaves) — the defining souring ingredient of Telugu cuisine — cooked with chicken or mutton creates the state's most beloved and distinctive non-vegetarian preparation. The leaves' tartness cuts through the fat of the meat and creates a depth of flavor impossible to replicate. Gongura chutney is on every AP table; Gongura mutton is the dish every Telugu person in the diaspora most misses."},
{emoji:"🥘",name:"Pappu (Dal) & Charu (Rasam)",region:"Statewide — Daily Food",desc:"The Telugu daily meal is built on pappu (lentil dal) and charu (pepper-tamarind rasam). Each district has its own pappu — tomato pappu, gongura pappu, raw mango pappu, greens pappu. Each meal begins with hot rice mixed with pappu and ghee; charu is drunk as a digestive. These seemingly simple preparations — each district's version distinct — represent the highest expression of Telugu home cooking."},
{emoji:"🍘",name:"Boorelu & Pootharekulu",region:"Festival Foods — Coastal AP",desc:"Boorelu — deep-fried sweet dumplings of rice flour filled with chana dal and jaggery paste — are the quintessential AP festival sweet, made for weddings and Sankranti. Pootharekulu — extraordinarily thin sheets of rice starch, dry as parchment paper, filled with powdered sugar and dry fruits — are an Atreyapuram specialty unique in Indian confectionery. The technique of making Pootharekulu sheets is one of the most delicate in Indian sweets."},
{emoji:"🌿",name:"Avakaya — AP Mango Pickle",region:"Statewide — GI Tagged",desc:"The most celebrated mango pickle in India — raw mango pieces marinated with Guntur chili powder, mustard seeds, salt and sesame oil in ceramic jars and aged for weeks. AP families make avakaya in enormous batches every May when raw mangoes arrive. Every Telugu household has its own avakaya recipe passed down through generations. The smell of avakaya being prepared fills entire neighborhoods in early summer."},
{emoji:"🥗",name:"Natu Kodi Pulusu & Seafood",region:"Coastal Andhra",desc:"Country chicken (natu kodi) slow-cooked in a tangy tamarind-based pulusu (sour gravy) with coconut and whole spices — the quintessential rural Andhra Sunday meal. Coastal AP's seafood — prawn pickle (royyala vepudu), crab curry, Kakinada crab fry and Machilipatnam fish preparations — represent some of South India's finest coastal cooking. The Bay of Bengal delivers extraordinary freshness."},
{emoji:"☕",name:"Araku Coffee",region:"Araku Valley, Visakhapatnam",desc:"One of India's finest specialty coffees — shade-grown by tribal farmers in the Eastern Ghats at 900–1,100 meters. Araku coffee won first prize at the Paris Coffee Championship in 2021. The tribal farming communities (Kondh, Koya, Bagata) grow it without chemicals using traditional methods. Smooth, chocolatey and lightly acidic — Araku is now served in premium coffee shops from Paris to Tokyo."},
{emoji:"🍬",name:"Pala Kova & Bandara Laddu",region:"Tirupati-Vijayawada",desc:"Tirupati Laddu — the sacred prasadam of Venkateswara Temple — is arguably the most famous sweet in India. Made from besan, ghee, sugar and cashews by the thousands daily, it is distributed to every pilgrim. Pala Kova (concentrated milk sweet from Vijayawada), Kakinada Kaja (layered milk pastry) and Badam Halwa from Kurnool complete AP's sweet tradition, which like everything else in this state runs rich and intense."}
